Deleting, and the careful use of rm dash-r.

This is the command to respect. rm, followed by a filename, deletes that file. There's no trash can, no undo. It's gone.

To delete a directory and everything inside it, you need the dash-r flag, for recursive. And to suppress prompts and remove even read-only files, you add dash-f, for force. Put them together and you get rm dash-r-f, which is the command that has taken down real production servers.

rm dash-r-f is genuinely dangerous. The infamous version, rm dash-r-f slash, tries to delete everything starting from the root of the filesystem. Modern rm refuses that exact command by default, but rm dash-r-f on someone's home directory still runs without a single word of warning.

So let's talk about habits that save you. First, rm dash-i asks before each delete. That's especially worth it when wildcards are involved: rm dash-i star-dot-log confirms each one.

Second, and this is the big one: list first, then delete. Before you run rm on star-dot-tmp, run ls on star-dot-tmp and look at exactly what matches. If the list looks right, press up-arrow to recall the line and change ls to rm. You get to see the blast radius before you pull the trigger.

Third, watch your variables. If you run rm dash-r-f on quote dollar-dir slash quote, and the dir variable happens to be empty, that command expands to rm dash-r-f slash. Exactly the disaster you don't want. Always check a variable's value before you delete through it.

And fourth, there's rmdir, which removes only an empty directory. When what you really mean is "this directory should be empty now, remove it," rmdir is a safer choice than rm dash-r, because it refuses if anything is still inside.

The bottom line: Linux has no built-in trash like macOS or Windows. Once rm runs, only specialised recovery tools have any chance of getting your data back, and even then, only sometimes.
